tflite: disambiguate std::abs for AbsEval/EvalImpl (Clang 21 / libc++)

Upstream (LLVM integration PR that included this hunk):
  https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/95894

Issue:
  AbsEval passes a callable into EvalImpl<T>, whose third parameter is
  std::function<T(T)>. Using std::abs<float> / std::abs<int32_t> here is
  brittle: std::abs is overloaded, and some toolchain combinations (e.g.
  Apple Clang 21 with the libc++ shipped in Xcode 26.4) no longer select a
  viable overload when constructing std::function, so the build fails.

Fix:
  Wrap the call in lambdas with exact signatures T(T) that forward to
  std::abs inside the lambda body, where overload resolution is
  straightforward.

API/ABI:
  No change to TensorFlow Lite public API or stable ABI for consumers.
  Internal kernel implementation only; supported types and operator
  semantics are unchanged.

--- a/tensorflow/lite/kernels/elementwise.cc
+++ b/tensorflow/lite/kernels/elementwise.cc
@@ -293,7 +293,8 @@
   const TfLiteType type = input->type;
   switch (type) {
     case kTfLiteFloat32:
-      return EvalImpl<float>(context, node, std::abs<float>, type);
+      return EvalImpl<float>(
+          context, node, [](float f) { return std::abs(f); }, type);
     case kTfLiteInt8:
       return AbsEvalQuantized<int8_t>(context, node, type);
     case kTfLiteInt16:
@@ -301,7 +302,8 @@
                  ? AbsInt16EvalImpl(context, node, type)
                  : AbsEvalQuantized<int16_t>(context, node, type);
     case kTfLiteInt32:
-      return EvalImpl<int32_t>(context, node, std::abs<int32_t>, type);
+      return EvalImpl<int32_t>(
+          context, node, [](int32_t i) { return std::abs(i); }, type);
     default:
       TF_LITE_KERNEL_LOG(context, "Current data type %s is not supported.",
                          TfLiteTypeGetName(type));
